A Proofs and Intermediate Results

The deﬁning properties LP1–LP3 of a coherent lower prevision imply various additional properties as well [10, Section 2.6.1]; we will need the following two in our proofs:

LP4. P(µ) = µ for all constant options µ ∈ R; LP5. P(u + µ) = P(u) + µ for all µ ∈ R and u ∈ L .
With any coherent lower prevision P, we can also associate a corresponding coherent upper prevision P, deﬁned by

P(u) := −P(−u) for all u ∈ L .

Linear previsions are lower previsions for which P and P coincide.
Proposition 4. [10, Section 2.3.6] A coherent lower prevision P on L is a linear prevision if and only P(u) = P(u) for all u ∈ L .

Lemma 1. For any P ∈ P, KP is coherent.

Proof. K0 and K1 hold because P(0) = 0 due to LP4. K2 holds because for any u ∈ L with inf u > 0, P(u) ≥ inf u > 0 due to LP1. Since K4 holds trivially, it remains to prove K3. So consider any A1, A2 ∈ KP and, for all u ∈ A1 and v ∈ A2, some (λu,v , µu,v) > 0. Since A1 ∈ KP , there is some u∗ ∈ A1 such that P(u∗) > 0. Similarly, there is some v∗ ∈ A2 such that P(v∗) > 0. It therefore follows from LP3 and LP2 that
P(λu∗,v∗ u∗ + µu∗,v∗ v∗) ≥ λu∗,v∗ P(u∗) + µu∗,v∗ P(v∗) > 0,

implying that

{λu,v u + µu,vv : u ∈ A1, v ∈ A2} ∈ KP .

⊓⊔

Proposition 5. Let K be an Archimedean set of desirable option sets. Then for any option set A ∈ Q such that A ∈/ K, there is a coherent lower prevision P ∈ P(K) such that A ∈/ KP .
Proof. Let K be an Archimedean set of desirable option sets and consider any option set A ∈ Q such that A ∈/ K.
Since K is Archimedean, we know from Deﬁnition 6 that there is some ε ∈ RK>0 such that A ∈/ Ex(Kε ). Because of Equation (6), this in turn implies that there must be some coherent set of desirable options D ∈ D such that A ∈/ KD and Kε ⊆ KD . For this coherent set of desirable options, we now consider the corresponding coherent lower prevision P, deﬁned by

P(u) := sup{µ ∈ R : u − µ ∈ D} for all u ∈ L .

(13)

That this functional P is indeed a coherent lower prevision is a standard result and follows easily from the coherence of D; see for example [10, Section 2.3.3]. It remains to show that A ∈/ KP and K ⊆ KP .

