since P ∈ P∗, this implies that there is some P ∈ P such that P(v − u) = P(v − u) ≤ 0 and therefore also P(u) ≥ P(v). Hence, u ∈ CPM(A). Conversely, assume that u ∈ CPM(A). For all v ∈ A \ {u}, this implies that there is some Pv ∈ P such that Pv(u) ≥ Pv(v) and therefore Pv(v − u) ≤ 0. Let P = minv∈A\{u} Pv. Then P ∈ P∗ because A \ {u} is ﬁnite and, for all v ∈ A \ {u}, P(v − u) ≤ Pv(v − u) ≤ 0. Hence, u ∈ CP∗(A). We conclude that u ∈ CP∗(A) if and only if u ∈ CPM(A). Since A ∈ Q and u ∈ A are arbitrary, this implies that, indeed, CP∗ = CPM.
It remains to show that P ⊆ P(KC). To that end, consider any P ∈ P and any A ∈ KC. Since A ∈ KC, we know that 0 ∈/ C(A ∪{0}). Since C = CPM, it therefore follows from Equation (3) that there is some v ∈ (A ∪{0})\{0} such that 0 = P(0) < P(v). Since (A ∪ {0}) \ {0} = A \ {0} ⊆ A, this implies that there is some v ∈ A such that P(v) > 0, meaning that A ∈ KP. Since A ∈ KC was arbitrary, this implies that KC ⊆ KP, hence P ∈ P(KC). Since P ∈ P was arbitrary, we ﬁnd that P is indeed a subset of P(KC). ⊓⊔
Proof of Proposition 3. First assume that CPE = CPM . Consider any two P1, P2 ∈ P and assume ex absurdo that P1 = P2. This implies that there is some u ∈ L such that P1(u) = P2(u). Without loss of generality, we can assume that P1(u) > P2(u) (otherwise, it sufﬁces to reverse the role of P1 and P2). Let u1 := P1(u) − u and u2 := u − P2(u) and consider the set A := {0, u1, u2}. It then follows from LP5 that P1(u2) = P1(u) − P2(u) > 0, P2(u1) = P1(u) − P2(u) > 0 and from LP4 that P1(0) = P2(0) = 0. Hence, u1 = 0 and u2 = 0, so A \ {0} = {u1, u2}. LP5 and LP4 also imply that P1(u1) = 0 = P1(0) and P2(u2) = 0 = P2(0). Since P1, P2 ∈ P, it therefore follows from Equation (3) that 0 ∈ CPM(A). Since CPE = CPM , this implies that 0 ∈ CPE (A), and therefore, because of Equation (2), that there is some P ∈ P such that, for all v ∈ A \ {0} = {u1, u2}, P(0) ≥ P(v). Due to the linearity of P and LP4, this implies that
P(u1 + u2) = P(u1) + P(u2) ≤ P(0) + P(0) = 0 + 0 = 0.
However, since u1 + u2 = P1(u) − u + u − P2(u) = P1(u) − P2(u), LP4 also implies that
P(u1 + u2) = P P1(u) − P2(u) = P1(u) − P2(u) > 0,
a contradiction. Hence, it must be that P1 = P2. Since this is true for any two P1, P2 ∈ P, and since P is non-empty, this implies that P consists of a single linear prevision P ∈ P: P = {P}.
Next, assume that there is a linear prevision P∈ P such that P = {P}. It then follows directly from Equation (2) and (3) that CPE = CPM.
Proof of Theorem 8. First assume that C is Archimedean, binary and mixing. Let P = P(KC). Since C is Archimedean and binary, it follows from Theorem 7 that C = CPM and that P is non-empty. Since C is Archimedean and mixing, it follows from Theorem 6 that C = CPE . Hence, CPE = CPM. Since P is non-empty, it therefore follows from Proposition 3 that there is a unique linear prevision P ∈ P such that P = {P}. Equations (1) and (2) now imply that C = CPE = CP.
Next, consider a linear prevision P ∈ P and let C = CP. Consider the set P = {P}. On the one hand, it then follows from Equations (1) and (2) that C = CP = CPE and therefore, because of Theorem 6, that C is Archimedean and mixing. On the other hand, it follows from Equations (1) and (3) that C = CP = CPM and therefore, because of Theorem 7, that C is binary.

